{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f27b2ad5-cb9e-4c0a-8bf1-4005ccd58bf7","content":"There's no workflow file in the current directory, so I'll give you the general guidance for switching to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC):\n\n### 1. Register your package on nuget.org for trusted publishing\n- Go to **nuget.org → Manage Package → Trusted Publishers**\n- Add your GitHub repository (owner, repo, optional branch/environment constraints)\n\n### 2. Update your GitHub Actions workflow\n\n**Remove:**\n```yaml\n- name: Push\n  run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg --api-key ${{ secrets.NUGET_API_KEY }} --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Replace with:**\n```yaml\npermissions:\n  id-token: write   # Required for OIDC token\n  contents: read\n\nsteps:\n  - name: Install .NET\n    uses: actions/setup-dotnet@v4\n\n  # ... your build/pack steps ...\n\n  - name: Push to NuGet (trusted publishing)\n    run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Key changes:\n| Before | After |\n|---|---|\n| `secrets.NUGET_API_KEY` | OIDC token (automatic) |\n| No special permissions | `id-token: write` required |\n| `--api-key` flag on push | Remove `--api-key` flag |\n\n### 3. Clean up\n- Delete the `NUGET_API_KEY` secret from your repo settings once verified.\n\nThe `dotnet nuget push` command (with .NET SDK 8.0.400+) automatically detects the GitHub OIDC token when `id-token: write` is set and the package is registered for trusted publishing on nuget.org — no API key needed.\n\nWant me to create a sample workflow file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9a276321-c743-4232-bdc5-9964307004e8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository appears to be empty. The user is asking a general question about switching from NuGet API key to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC). Let me provide guidance based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":499,"requestId":"0406:B994F:4B3905:572E2F:69F00569"},"id":"ab11d7a1-85fc-4c00-9d76-a91e7